56
00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:14.269
Thank you, Dr Ferre, for the very generous introduction, and good morning,

57
00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:17.980
everyone. And I'd like to thank San Antonio Breast Cancer

58
00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:21.340
Conference for the invitation, as well as AACR. It's great to be in San Diego.

59
00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:25.800
So I'm going to be talking about some of our recent research to try and understand

60
00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:29.460
how reproductive events change immune responses

61
00:03:30.300 --> 00:03:31.820
with regards to breast cancer.

62
00:03:34.020 --> 00:03:36.720
These are my disclosures, none of which are relevant today.

63
00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:42.840
Okay, so as background, breast cancer has not traditionally been considered

64
00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:46.800
immunogenic, but now we have large bodies of evidence which highlight the role of

65
00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:48.740
immunity and specifically T cells,

66
00:03:49.700 --> 00:03:52.460
and an active role in breast cancer growth and progression.

67
00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:56.800
The proof of the pudding, of course, is now that we use pembrolizumab, a T

68
00:03:56.880 --> 00:04:00.820
cell checkpoint inhibitor, with chemotherapy in patients with

69
00:04:01.180 --> 00:04:05.020
both early and late triple-negative breast cancer due

70
00:04:05.060 --> 00:04:08.840
to significant improvements in overall survival, as shown on the

71
00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:12.740
right there. But we still have limited understanding of the women who

72
00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:16.620
derive the most benefit from these T cell or T cell checkpoint

73
00:04:16.661 --> 00:04:17.671
targeting therapies.

74
00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:23.130
So one way we've been trying to stratify patients into groups that

75
00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:26.880
respond better to these type of treatments is by using the

76
00:04:26.940 --> 00:04:29.400
immune infiltration in breast cancer.

77
00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:34.000
Using this method we developed now well over 10 years ago, quantifying immune

78
00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:36.500
infiltration in H&amp;E stained slides.

79
00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:40.190
We and others have shown that the quantity of immune infiltrations is really

80
00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:43.960
important in outcomes of these patients, and specifically for

81
00:04:43.980 --> 00:04:45.620
triple-negative breast cancer patients.

82
00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:49.720
And they have a strong role with regards to prognosis

83
00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:53.840
in the setting of no therapy, chemotherapy, and now in the

84
00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:56.770
context of neoadjuvant chemotherapy and immunotherapy.

85
00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:01.300
They also have a role in prediction of response in advanced disease as

86
00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:05.040
well. But we still, again, have very limited understanding of

87
00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:09.400
the women, why they have high and low levels of immune infiltrate, and also the

88
00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:13.260
molecular characteristics of the high infiltration, which is

89
00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:16.020
associated with better responses to these treatments.

90
00:05:17.730 --> 00:05:21.550
So we started studying the heterogeneity in the T cell infiltrates,

91
00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:25.420
specifically in patients that had higher levels of this immune infiltration

92
00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:28.660
because they did better to try and ask the question, what are the molecular

93
00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:30.960
characteristics of this immune infiltrate?

94
00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:34.940
We did this using single cell sequencing, and as well as

95
00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:38.960
observing a very distinct large amount of molecular

96
00:05:38.980 --> 00:05:42.920
heterogeneity. We were very interested in one subset of T cells,

97
00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:46.980
expressed high levels of checkpoints such as PD-1,

98
00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:51.820
TIM-3, for example, which was important back then because we were still developing

99
00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:53.300
these therapies in breast cancer.

100
00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:57.620
It also had markers of perforin and granzyme, which

101
00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:01.010
suggested they were cytotoxic and mediated tumor killing.

102
00:06:01.460 --> 00:06:05.220
But importantly, they also had markers that were characteristic of what we

103
00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:08.980
understand were features of residency, and these

104
00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:12.628
include-Decreased expression of these markers down here,

105
00:06:12.968 --> 00:06:16.948
but also increased expression of this integrin here, ITGAE or

106
00:06:17.008 --> 00:06:20.608
CD103. And CD103 is important because it forms a

107
00:06:20.628 --> 00:06:24.568
heterodimer and binds onto ecaderin, which is a molecule which

108
00:06:24.608 --> 00:06:28.168
is widely expressed on breast cancer epithelial cells.

109
00:06:28.208 --> 00:06:32.108
So this suggested to us that this T cell subset was localized

110
00:06:32.148 --> 00:06:35.688
to the breast epithelium and could help mediate a better anti-tumor

111
00:06:35.748 --> 00:06:36.328
response.

112
00:06:37.508 --> 00:06:40.588
So what do we know about TRMs or tissue resident memory T cells?

113
00:06:41.028 --> 00:06:44.748
So back then, they were well-characterized in the literature, infection literature

114
00:06:44.828 --> 00:06:48.788
mainly. These are memory T cells, so we have circulating memory T cells.

115
00:06:49.128 --> 00:06:52.868
But when we're exposed to a pathogen, for example, virus, flu, or

116
00:06:52.928 --> 00:06:56.908
COVID, we generate memory T cells, and some of these memory

117
00:06:56.968 --> 00:07:00.758
T cells stay in the organ that was initially exposed

118
00:07:00.948 --> 00:07:04.688
to that infection. So these T cells acquire what we call markers of

119
00:07:04.748 --> 00:07:08.108
residency. They stay located in, for example, in that

120
00:07:08.528 --> 00:07:11.388
example with a lung. And next time you re-expose this

121
00:07:11.408 --> 00:07:15.058
pathogen, they provide an immediate and

122
00:07:15.208 --> 00:07:17.468
very robust defense against that pathogen.

123
00:07:18.068 --> 00:07:21.388
Such is the case that you may not actually have any symptoms of being reinfected

124
00:07:21.408 --> 00:07:22.478
with that pathogen again.

125
00:07:23.308 --> 00:07:27.108
So these T cells are robust. They form immediate defense.

126
00:07:27.148 --> 00:07:31.118
They also remain in the tissue despite having no antigen

127
00:07:31.228 --> 00:07:35.038
there. And they also have high markers of checkpoints, which suggests that

128
00:07:35.068 --> 00:07:39.058
these are not exhausted T cells, but potentially could be targeted by similar

129
00:07:39.068 --> 00:07:42.008
therapies. So in the cancer setting, we

130
00:07:43.548 --> 00:07:45.108
thought that they could be important.

131
00:07:45.208 --> 00:07:48.848
And as supportive of this Kaplan-Meier curve, when we looked at a

132
00:07:48.988 --> 00:07:52.668
signature that was just taken from these TRM

133
00:07:52.728 --> 00:07:56.718
cells and compared it to just a generic CD8 gene expression,

134
00:07:56.768 --> 00:08:00.548
we found that the TRM signature provided

135
00:08:00.568 --> 00:08:02.428
better prognostication, suggesting that this

136
00:08:03.468 --> 00:08:07.248
representation of a localized immune response also represented a

137
00:08:07.268 --> 00:08:10.888
systemic anti-tumor immune response that could protect against distant

138
00:08:10.928 --> 00:08:11.408
recurrence.

139
00:08:12.328 --> 00:08:15.308
We then went on to model this in a mouse to try and understand if they could

140
00:08:15.848 --> 00:08:19.747
respond to checkpoint blockade. And we found that in this mouse tumor

141
00:08:19.807 --> 00:08:23.268
model that they could. And interestingly, what we found in the mice that were

142
00:08:23.288 --> 00:08:26.848
treated with checkpoint blockade, that there were 60% of the mice that cleared

143
00:08:26.868 --> 00:08:28.508
their tumors from their mammary fat pad.

144
00:08:28.848 --> 00:08:32.828
And we found that these TRM-like cells remain in the mammary fat pad that

145
00:08:32.908 --> 00:08:34.288
was free of tumor.

146
00:08:35.268 --> 00:08:39.188
So then we asked the question: Could these T cells provide protection against

147
00:08:39.509 --> 00:08:43.148
tumor rechallenge? And so we did this in the setting of an agent called

148
00:08:43.249 --> 00:08:47.048
FTY720. And what this does is inhibits the T

149
00:08:47.128 --> 00:08:50.788
cells from the lymph nodes, so we can just see the effect of the T cells

150
00:08:50.808 --> 00:08:52.668
within the localized area.

151
00:08:53.728 --> 00:08:57.508
So we did the experiment for these mice. We rechallenged the mice with tumor.

152
00:08:58.028 --> 00:09:01.948
And what we found in the local mammary fat pad that was originally exposed to the

153
00:09:02.028 --> 00:09:05.868
tumor, we found that this mammary fat pad was protected from tumor

154
00:09:05.908 --> 00:09:09.528
rechallenge in the setting of FTY, which suggested that these

155
00:09:09.648 --> 00:09:12.808
local T cells could proliferate, expand, and provide anti-tumor

156
00:09:12.888 --> 00:09:16.798
protection, as you can see here. But interestingly, in

157
00:09:16.828 --> 00:09:20.808
the contralateral mammary fat pad that had never been exposed to tumor

158
00:09:20.877 --> 00:09:24.788
cells, we also saw protection there as well, suggesting that we

159
00:09:24.848 --> 00:09:28.508
had a localized memory response, but also a systemic

160
00:09:28.628 --> 00:09:32.168
anti-tumor response that could protect against distant recurrence.

161
00:09:32.488 --> 00:09:36.428
And the fact that these TRM cells were present in the normal mammary

162
00:09:36.468 --> 00:09:40.228
fat pad without any tumor suggested that these were very similar to

163
00:09:40.388 --> 00:09:42.348
the TRM cells we saw in infection.

164
00:09:43.528 --> 00:09:45.698
But that, of course, led us to the question,

165
00:09:46.628 --> 00:09:46.768
if

166
00:09:47.828 --> 00:09:51.748
these TRM cells could remain in the normal mammary fat pad without tumor, does this

167
00:09:51.788 --> 00:09:55.528
happen also in humans? So next, we looked at human normal

168
00:09:55.568 --> 00:09:58.508
breasts. So this was cancer-unaffected normal breast.

169
00:09:58.888 --> 00:10:00.448
And we found that indeed,

170
00:10:01.368 --> 00:10:05.068
not in the same quantities as in primary tumors, in this case,

171
00:10:05.108 --> 00:10:08.678
triple-negative breast cancer, but in normal breast that was cancer unaffected, as

172
00:10:08.708 --> 00:10:12.268
you can see there, there's a significant number of T cells present in

173
00:10:12.288 --> 00:10:16.058
the breast tissue. And these T cells express this

174
00:10:16.068 --> 00:10:19.908
resident memory phenotype that we were interested in.

175
00:10:19.928 --> 00:10:22.688
So that begs the question, these are normal breast.

176
00:10:22.888 --> 00:10:26.438
This is a normal, healthy breast. Why are there T cells in a normal, healthy

177
00:10:26.508 --> 00:10:30.388
breast? And do they have a part to play in immune surveillance and breast

178
00:10:30.468 --> 00:10:31.388
cancer protection?

179
00:10:33.048 --> 00:10:36.648
So this, of course, led us to try and look at the role of

180
00:10:36.688 --> 00:10:40.188
pregnancy and breastfeeding. So we know that breast cancer is rising

181
00:10:40.248 --> 00:10:43.068
globally in the world, specifically in younger women.

182
00:10:43.558 --> 00:10:47.108
A lot of this risk is thought to be related to changing in reproductive

183
00:10:47.508 --> 00:10:48.548
lifestyles and also

184
00:10:49.608 --> 00:10:53.548
decreasing age of menarche. The risk is highest in women that

185
00:10:53.568 --> 00:10:57.248
are non-childbearing and lowest in women who have children and breastfed, and this

186
00:10:57.288 --> 00:10:59.188
has been observed for many centuries, actually.

187
00:10:59.868 --> 00:11:03.428
The mechanisms have largely been thought to be related to hormones and changes in

188
00:11:03.468 --> 00:11:07.208
the breast structure, post-pregnancy and breastfeeding. And this risk is nuanced.

189
00:11:07.548 --> 00:11:11.408
Your risk of breast cancer does rise immediately postpartum, but ultimately becomes

190
00:11:11.428 --> 00:11:14.888
protective the longer from your last child.

191
00:11:14.928 --> 00:11:15.818
And you can see here in this

192
00:11:16.708 --> 00:11:20.278
meta-analysis from "The Lancet," for every child, your risk of breast cancer is

193
00:11:20.288 --> 00:11:24.128
reduced by 7% and a further reduction for every 12

194
00:11:24.168 --> 00:11:25.068
months of breastfeeding.

195
00:11:26.328 --> 00:11:30.008
But as we've understood about breast cancer subtypes, what we've realized is that

196
00:11:30.068 --> 00:11:33.968
this breastfeeding effect seems very specific to triple-negative

197
00:11:33.988 --> 00:11:37.828
breast cancer. So you can see here, the longer duration you've breastfed, the

198
00:11:37.948 --> 00:11:41.858
lower your risk of triple-negative breast cancer, and this doesn't seem to be the

199
00:11:41.948 --> 00:11:45.888
case for the hormone-responsive tumors, where age at first birth seems to

200
00:11:45.948 --> 00:11:49.748
be most important. So this got us thinking, triple-negative breast cancer,

201
00:11:49.808 --> 00:11:52.428
high amounts of T cell infiltrate. We use pembrolizumab.

202
00:11:53.528 --> 00:11:54.208
Is this

203
00:11:55.108 --> 00:11:57.548
what we're observing here related to T cells?

204
00:11:59.008 --> 00:12:02.732
So then we ask the questionAt the start, DOOP

205
00:12:02.792 --> 00:12:06.752
women who'd had children had more T cells in their normal cancer unaffected

206
00:12:06.832 --> 00:12:10.812
breast. So we did this in two ways. We looked at women of average risk

207
00:12:10.872 --> 00:12:14.612
who'd had breast reductions, and we also looked at women of high risk who'd had

208
00:12:14.652 --> 00:12:18.492
prophylactic mastectomies. So up here, we looked at single cell RNA

209
00:12:18.532 --> 00:12:22.322
seq data from women who had breast reductions, and as you can see here in

210
00:12:22.392 --> 00:12:25.392
orange, in the Paris women, there are high numbers of immune

211
00:12:25.412 --> 00:12:29.202
cells, high number of T cells, CD8 T cells,

212
00:12:29.552 --> 00:12:32.092
and specifically our TRM phenotype of interest.

213
00:12:32.442 --> 00:12:36.232
And similarly, in women who are high risk, who'd had prophylactic mastectomies, so

214
00:12:36.312 --> 00:12:40.172
usually germline carriers, again, we see a significantly high levels of immune

215
00:12:40.252 --> 00:12:43.532
cells, CD3 positive T cells, and again, this

216
00:12:43.572 --> 00:12:47.452
TRM phenotype of interest in this normal

217
00:12:47.572 --> 00:12:48.792
cancer unaffected breast.

218
00:12:49.872 --> 00:12:53.782
Using OPAL, you can see that these little dots representing the TRM cells, and

219
00:12:53.812 --> 00:12:57.432
this is the Paris normal breast and the nulliparous breast, and you can see many

220
00:12:57.472 --> 00:13:00.972
more of these dots in the Paris breast, and they're closer to the ductal

221
00:13:01.032 --> 00:13:03.772
epithelium, suggesting they have a role in immune surveillance.

222
00:13:04.252 --> 00:13:06.892
And just of note that these cells are very long-lived.

223
00:13:06.932 --> 00:13:10.552
We had some samples that were 30 years from their last child, and these T

224
00:13:10.652 --> 00:13:14.172
cells were still present, suggesting that these T cells can exist in the

225
00:13:14.232 --> 00:13:16.112
breast for a very long period of time.

226
00:13:17.632 --> 00:13:21.592
So next question we asked was, so we've made this observation in women,

227
00:13:22.532 --> 00:13:26.412
can we model this in a mouse? So the first thing we asked was, can we see

228
00:13:26.592 --> 00:13:28.292
similar findings in a mouse model?

229
00:13:28.912 --> 00:13:32.492
So we used a model of a mouse that

230
00:13:32.552 --> 00:13:36.292
had pups and that had undergone full lactation and

231
00:13:36.352 --> 00:13:39.382
involution. So in a mouse, lactation is around 21 days,

232
00:13:39.912 --> 00:13:43.662
this is just the average period. Then

233
00:13:43.732 --> 00:13:47.512
the pups are removed, and the mammary fat pad undergoes

234
00:13:47.532 --> 00:13:51.292
involution, and by day 28 post-involution, the mammary fat pad has

235
00:13:51.332 --> 00:13:55.052
returned to looking histologically like the pre-pregnancy state.

236
00:13:55.492 --> 00:13:59.412
So we compared the immune cell components of these two conditions, and

237
00:13:59.432 --> 00:14:03.402
what we found was really the only main immune cell that was increased in

238
00:14:03.432 --> 00:14:07.302
the day 28 model were the mammary T cells, and

239
00:14:07.452 --> 00:14:11.241
as you can see here. And these T cells, there was a higher level of T cells,

240
00:14:11.472 --> 00:14:15.211
higher amount of T cells that express this TRM phenotype.

241
00:14:16.232 --> 00:14:19.672
As a control, we also looked at a model of an earlier

242
00:14:19.681 --> 00:14:23.652
postpartum time point, and this time point has been quite well characterized in

243
00:14:23.672 --> 00:14:25.842
the literature because it's associated with poorer outcomes.

244
00:14:26.212 --> 00:14:29.782
This is thought to be related to the macrophage content at this time,

245
00:14:30.292 --> 00:14:31.762
this forced involution time point.

246
00:14:32.072 --> 00:14:36.022
And indeed, we did see a high level of macrophages at this time point,

247
00:14:36.372 --> 00:14:40.212
and only very slightly higher levels of CD8 and nowhere near the magnitude that we

248
00:14:40.272 --> 00:14:41.772
saw in the day 208.

249
00:14:42.812 --> 00:14:45.912
Visually, again, you can see this in the OPAL images.

250
00:14:46.172 --> 00:14:50.092
You can see here in this day 28 model here, the mammary fat pad, all the

251
00:14:50.132 --> 00:14:54.032
little dots representing a significantly high amount of TRM-like cells compared

252
00:14:54.092 --> 00:14:55.052
to the virgin mouse.

253
00:14:55.992 --> 00:14:59.532
So then the next question we asked was, now we've seen this increase in the immune

254
00:14:59.572 --> 00:15:03.252
content of T cells, is it functional? Can it restrain tumor growth?

255
00:15:03.652 --> 00:15:07.052
So we implanted tumor cells at these same time points.

256
00:15:08.332 --> 00:15:11.852
And what we found was in the day 10 time point, the forced wean time point, where

257
00:15:11.892 --> 00:15:15.572
we saw the macrophage infiltrate, we saw no difference in

258
00:15:15.652 --> 00:15:19.572
the tumors that grew when implanted at these time points compared to virgin.

259
00:15:20.312 --> 00:15:24.192
In contrast, however, at the day 28 time point, so the mice that had undergone

260
00:15:24.252 --> 00:15:28.012
full lactation and involution, we saw significantly smaller tumors

261
00:15:28.292 --> 00:15:30.392
at this endpoint, as you can see there.

262
00:15:31.552 --> 00:15:35.192
So this T cell difference does seem to have a functional impact on tumor

263
00:15:35.252 --> 00:15:35.612
growth.

264
00:15:36.612 --> 00:15:38.652
What is the till content within these tumors?

265
00:15:38.732 --> 00:15:42.582
As we know in humans, higher amounts of immune infiltrate has

266
00:15:42.712 --> 00:15:43.272
prognostic

267
00:15:45.532 --> 00:15:49.092
implications. And you can see at this day 28 time point here that

268
00:15:49.152 --> 00:15:52.592
these tumors have higher levels of CD8 positive T cells.

269
00:15:52.992 --> 00:15:56.832
There's more over positive, so more antigen positive T cells.

270
00:15:57.222 --> 00:16:00.982
These T cells express PD-1, and there's higher amounts of

271
00:16:01.032 --> 00:16:04.852
this type one DC. So these subsets of course, are

272
00:16:04.892 --> 00:16:08.562
very important in mediating response to pembrolizumab or T cell

273
00:16:08.612 --> 00:16:11.632
checkpoint therapies. So not only are the

274
00:16:13.712 --> 00:16:17.492
tumors smaller at this time point, they had more T cell content.

275
00:16:17.512 --> 00:16:21.332
And then finally, we asked the question, is this protection or smaller

276
00:16:21.392 --> 00:16:25.232
tumors that we're seeing specifically related to CD8 positive T

277
00:16:25.352 --> 00:16:29.232
cells? So to try and help us to understand this specific

278
00:16:29.332 --> 00:16:32.932
mechanism, we use RAG mice. So RAG mice lack

279
00:16:33.012 --> 00:16:36.172
NK, T, and B cells. We use the same time points.

280
00:16:36.552 --> 00:16:40.372
And what we found was that we lost protection in the day 28

281
00:16:40.672 --> 00:16:43.972
mouse. See here, the tumors are exactly the same size.

282
00:16:44.352 --> 00:16:48.172
So this implies that this benefit we see in the Paris mouse is

283
00:16:48.192 --> 00:16:49.572
immune cell dependent.

284
00:16:50.952 --> 00:16:54.912
The next thing we did was in this RAG mouse, we injected CD8 positive T

285
00:16:55.032 --> 00:16:58.632
cells that recognize OVA. And we did this at the day

286
00:16:58.732 --> 00:17:02.492
28, day 10 time points. And what we found that in the day

287
00:17:02.692 --> 00:17:05.852
28 time point, that this protection was restored.

288
00:17:06.052 --> 00:17:09.633
And you can see there, this is quite impressive tumor reduction at this

289
00:17:09.652 --> 00:17:10.633
particular time point

290
00:17:12.192 --> 00:17:16.123
associated with an increased number of these TRM-like cells at

291
00:17:16.152 --> 00:17:19.972
this time point as well. In contrast, at the earlier time point, the day 10,

292
00:17:20.252 --> 00:17:23.312
we see no difference in tumor size.

293
00:17:23.932 --> 00:17:27.633
So this tells us that adoptive CD8 positive T cells

294
00:17:27.712 --> 00:17:31.692
into RAG mice can return the protection that we

295
00:17:31.832 --> 00:17:32.752
saw originally in the

296
00:17:33.752 --> 00:17:34.782
immune competent mouse.

297
00:17:35.812 --> 00:17:37.992
And then the next thing we did was CD8 depletions.

298
00:17:38.012 --> 00:17:40.192
We did both alpha and beta depletions.

299
00:17:40.892 --> 00:17:44.212
And as you can see here that the four and eight depletion,

300
00:17:45.072 --> 00:17:49.032
we lose protection. So this phenocopies the virgin mouse, and we lose

301
00:17:49.092 --> 00:17:52.992
protection with both alpha and beta depletions, suggesting that this protection

302
00:17:53.072 --> 00:17:56.612
is reliant on conventional CD8 positive T cells and

303
00:17:56.652 --> 00:18:00.496
not innate-like T cells.And then finally, we

304
00:18:00.536 --> 00:18:03.296
looked at the effect using this molecule

305
00:18:03.716 --> 00:18:07.656
FTY720. So as you might recall, this really allows us

306
00:18:07.696 --> 00:18:11.656
to dissect the contribution of the local versus the circulating memory T

307
00:18:11.856 --> 00:18:14.646
cells. And what we found was, unlike the tumor model

308
00:18:15.236 --> 00:18:19.136
previously, we found that we lose protection in the parous

309
00:18:19.256 --> 00:18:22.436
mouse, as you can see there, compared to control.

310
00:18:22.496 --> 00:18:26.476
So this suggests that not only are the local T cells important, but

311
00:18:26.556 --> 00:18:29.316
it recruits circulating memory T cells.

312
00:18:29.596 --> 00:18:33.565
And it does suggest that actually not only does the local immunity change, but

313
00:18:33.616 --> 00:18:37.316
the systemic immune system also changes in the parous

314
00:18:37.376 --> 00:18:37.716
mouse.

315
00:18:40.076 --> 00:18:42.536
So, the next thing we asked was about breastfeeding.

316
00:18:42.636 --> 00:18:46.156
It's very hard to deconvolute breastfeeding in the mouse model, so we went back to

317
00:18:46.216 --> 00:18:50.036
patients, and we asked, is it associated with

318
00:18:50.716 --> 00:18:52.296
further breast cancer protection

319
00:18:53.156 --> 00:18:54.356
over parity alone?

320
00:18:55.536 --> 00:18:59.256
For this, we look far and wide actually for datasets that had collected

321
00:19:00.076 --> 00:19:01.636
information on parity and breastfeeding.

322
00:19:01.656 --> 00:19:05.576
This is actually quite hard to find, so I ask you all to collect this now more

323
00:19:05.616 --> 00:19:06.876
systematically in your patients.

324
00:19:07.436 --> 00:19:11.416
But this Malaysian dataset had collected parity and breastfeeding history

325
00:19:12.056 --> 00:19:14.756
in women who developed breast cancer after their last child.

326
00:19:15.156 --> 00:19:18.656
And what we found was in the triple-negative breast cancer patients,

327
00:19:19.046 --> 00:19:20.836
their tumors, if they had

328
00:19:22.556 --> 00:19:26.536
children and had longer duration breastfeeding, they had higher levels of

329
00:19:26.576 --> 00:19:30.296
immune infiltration compared to nulliparous women, this in quite

330
00:19:30.396 --> 00:19:32.296
specific to triple-negative breast cancer.

331
00:19:32.786 --> 00:19:36.416
And using spatial OPA, we found that this T cell

332
00:19:36.476 --> 00:19:40.076
content was more intratumoral in the patients in the women who had

333
00:19:40.816 --> 00:19:41.376
breastfed.

334
00:19:42.976 --> 00:19:46.756
Next, we looked at women of high risk, so BRCA carriers who developed also

335
00:19:46.856 --> 00:19:48.356
breast cancer after their last child.

336
00:19:48.796 --> 00:19:52.626
And you can see here that not only was the duration of breastfeeding associated

337
00:19:52.636 --> 00:19:56.236
with higher levels of TIL infiltrating the tumors, but this seemed to mediate

338
00:19:56.256 --> 00:19:59.456
improved survival in this cohort of high-risk women.

339
00:19:59.496 --> 00:20:03.396
So breastfeeding was associated with improved survival as well as higher TIL

340
00:20:03.496 --> 00:20:07.096
infiltrate, suggesting that longer breastfeeding duration adds

341
00:20:07.176 --> 00:20:09.735
further immune protection for these women.

342
00:20:11.156 --> 00:20:14.816
So in summary, our findings show that parity and

343
00:20:14.856 --> 00:20:18.336
breastfeeding and involution reshape the normal and breast immune

344
00:20:18.376 --> 00:20:22.296
landscape. This immune remodeling results in accumulation of CD8

345
00:20:22.336 --> 00:20:26.186
T cells within the breast. It's probably evolved as

346
00:20:26.236 --> 00:20:28.216
to protect the mother against infection.

347
00:20:28.556 --> 00:20:32.396
But in the cancer context, this results in enhanced immune

348
00:20:32.476 --> 00:20:36.176
surveillance, better recruitment of circulating T cells in case of tumor

349
00:20:36.216 --> 00:20:39.736
development, smaller tumors, and more tumoral immune

350
00:20:39.796 --> 00:20:43.726
infiltration. So we conclude that reproductive history is important in shaping

351
00:20:43.756 --> 00:20:46.245
the immune biology of the breast and the mother

352
00:20:47.076 --> 00:20:50.236
for protection against specifically triple-negative breast cancer.

353
00:20:51.836 --> 00:20:55.276
So in conclusion, immunotherapy is now standard of care for patients with

354
00:20:55.316 --> 00:20:59.016
triple-negative breast cancer. Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes or

355
00:20:59.096 --> 00:21:02.516
TIL in the tumor reflect more than just tumor mutational burden.

356
00:21:02.916 --> 00:21:06.305
The immune microenvironment is shaped not only by neoantigens but by host

357
00:21:06.356 --> 00:21:06.996
physiology.

358
00:21:07.996 --> 00:21:11.626
Parity, breastfeeding, and involution remodel the normal breast and

359
00:21:11.716 --> 00:21:15.596
systemic immunity of the mother to provide durable CD8-mediated

360
00:21:15.656 --> 00:21:18.416
T cell protection against triple-negative breast cancer.

361
00:21:18.446 --> 00:21:21.496
And we believe these data provide a mechanism for the long-standing

362
00:21:21.576 --> 00:21:25.116
epidemiological observation of this association.

363
00:21:25.956 --> 00:21:29.556
Reproductive history, specifically duration of breastfeeding, should be collected

364
00:21:29.596 --> 00:21:33.276
in all future breast cancer immuno-oncology trials.

365
00:21:33.296 --> 00:21:36.636
And our data suggests that women will have variable responses to

366
00:21:36.696 --> 00:21:39.696
immunotherapy depending on their parity and breastfeeding history.

367
00:21:40.656 --> 00:21:44.636
Translating parity-driven pathways could yield therapeutic strategies for both

368
00:21:44.676 --> 00:21:47.576
prevention and treatment. So hopefully, women,

369
00:21:49.676 --> 00:21:52.776
if they don't choose to have children or breastfeed, we can mimic and provide

370
00:21:52.996 --> 00:21:55.836
therapeutic interventions that are similar.

371
00:21:56.466 --> 00:22:00.396
And finally, our data highlights the importance of normal breast

372
00:22:00.576 --> 00:22:04.316
tissue immune health, and this is actually a modifier or

373
00:22:04.356 --> 00:22:05.976
determinant of tumor control.

374
00:22:07.576 --> 00:22:09.856
So with that, I'd like to thank you for your attention.

375
00:22:09.896 --> 00:22:13.646
I'd like to specifically highlight the four postdocs that worked on this

376
00:22:14.016 --> 00:22:17.456
project. My collaborator, Laura McKay at Peter Mac,

377
00:22:17.536 --> 00:22:21.296
specifically, and other collaborators, Paul Neeson and Phil Darcy from Peter

378
00:22:21.305 --> 00:22:24.736
Mac, and also Jee Win Pan from the Malaysian Cancer Institute,

379
00:22:25.236 --> 00:22:28.116
and of course, my funding bodies, and thank you for your attention.

380
00:22:34.956 --> 00:22:37.776
So we have time and encourage questions from the audience.

381
00:22:37.896 --> 00:22:41.596
If you have a question, please come up to one of the two microphones here.

382
00:22:41.656 --> 00:22:42.176
Please go ahead.

