led this work, April Watt and Antonio Arn.

490
00:28:04.848 --> 00:28:08.808
And I'd also like to acknowledge the rest of our team, and importantly,

491
00:28:08.888 --> 00:28:12.688
the various funding bodies that have supported the work I'm going to present to you

492
00:28:12.728 --> 00:28:13.108
today.

493
00:28:15.268 --> 00:28:19.048
So just to briefly reorient you to Rb, I think as you all know,

494
00:28:19.248 --> 00:28:22.388
Rb is a canonical tumor suppressor protein.

495
00:28:22.448 --> 00:28:25.568
In fact, it was the first tumor suppressor to ever be discovered.

496
00:28:26.508 --> 00:28:30.248
And in that role, Rb essentially enforces

497
00:28:30.548 --> 00:28:34.008
cell cycle arrest in the G1 phase of the cell cycle.

498
00:28:34.648 --> 00:28:38.588
Basically, when Rb is active, it represses the E2F

499
00:28:38.598 --> 00:28:41.788
transcription factors, and it prevents the expression of

500
00:28:41.808 --> 00:28:44.748
genes that are required for entry into S phase.

501
00:28:46.148 --> 00:28:49.908
And it's become very interesting to study Rb again recently

502
00:28:49.928 --> 00:28:53.198
because now we have drugs that can

503
00:28:53.288 --> 00:28:56.938
selectively and directly activate this

504
00:28:56.968 --> 00:29:00.808
repressive function of Rb. Of course, I'm talking about the CDK4/6

505
00:29:00.868 --> 00:29:04.788
inhibitors. These drugs work by preventing the phosphorylation of

506
00:29:04.948 --> 00:29:08.677
Rb, driving it to the chromatin where it binds to and

507
00:29:08.788 --> 00:29:12.568
represses the E2F factors and induces G1

508
00:29:12.588 --> 00:29:16.558
cell cycle arrest. And we know that this principle is exactly what

509
00:29:16.588 --> 00:29:18.848
happens in patients because we have a series of

510
00:29:20.068 --> 00:29:23.998
older studies where these drugs were used as monotherapy, and

511
00:29:24.188 --> 00:29:27.668
it was shown in hormone receptor-positive tumors that CDK4/6

512
00:29:27.708 --> 00:29:31.528
inhibitors do indeed reduce the phosphorylation of Rb.

513
00:29:31.588 --> 00:29:35.518
They do reduce indices of tumor cell proliferation, and

514
00:29:35.548 --> 00:29:39.528
they do repress the expression of E2F target genes in

515
00:29:39.568 --> 00:29:40.008
tumors.

516
00:29:41.368 --> 00:29:44.768
But there's a bit of a disconnect, I think, because as monotherapy,

517
00:29:45.428 --> 00:29:49.368
despite those findings, we know that these drugs in the clinic have fairly

518
00:29:49.378 --> 00:29:53.228
modest activity. And the real clinical impact and benefit

519
00:29:53.238 --> 00:29:56.828
that we've seen has always come when they've been combined with endocrine

520
00:29:56.848 --> 00:30:00.668
therapy. And it kind of raises a pretty simple question, I guess, which

521
00:30:00.748 --> 00:30:04.408
is, if activating Rb with these drugs is so good at

522
00:30:04.428 --> 00:30:08.228
suppressing proliferation, why isn't that enough on its

523
00:30:08.268 --> 00:30:12.088
own?So that's not the exact question that

524
00:30:12.128 --> 00:30:14.608
we posed when we started this work,

525
00:30:15.468 --> 00:30:17.208
but it will become relevant in my talk.

526
00:30:17.608 --> 00:30:21.428
We actually started by asking a broader, more unbiased question.

527
00:30:21.728 --> 00:30:25.288
What we really asked is, when we activate Rb with a CDK4/6

528
00:30:25.328 --> 00:30:29.218
inhibitor, well, we know it's going to E2F transcription factors

529
00:30:29.248 --> 00:30:32.138
at cell cycle gene promoters and repressing those genes,

530
00:30:33.068 --> 00:30:36.068
but what else is Rb doing on the chromatin?

531
00:30:36.608 --> 00:30:40.258
There is some older literature, 20, 30 years old, suggesting that

532
00:30:40.388 --> 00:30:44.188
Rb might be able to bind other transcription factors or other chromatin

533
00:30:44.248 --> 00:30:48.028
modifiers to influence other gene expression programs, but

534
00:30:48.088 --> 00:30:50.268
this all comes from the pre-genomic era.

535
00:30:51.118 --> 00:30:55.008
And what Rb is doing on the chromatin in cancer

536
00:30:55.028 --> 00:30:58.808
cells once it's been drug activated has essentially

537
00:30:58.868 --> 00:31:01.088
never been explored before.

538
00:31:03.068 --> 00:31:05.388
And so despite how critical Rb is

539
00:31:06.268 --> 00:31:09.858
in this disease, we actually have no clear picture of what it does on the

540
00:31:09.908 --> 00:31:13.868
chromatin in these cancer cells, except for repressing the cell cycle.

541
00:31:13.928 --> 00:31:17.878
I think one of the main reasons we don't know this is because to study this

542
00:31:17.908 --> 00:31:21.488
question, one would need to map Rb on the chromatin genome-wide using

543
00:31:21.528 --> 00:31:25.088
techniques such as ChIP-seq. And that has just

544
00:31:25.128 --> 00:31:29.068
been notoriously very difficult from a technical standpoint for those of

545
00:31:29.108 --> 00:31:32.688
us who work in this field. And so it remains this black

546
00:31:32.828 --> 00:31:36.758
box actually in the field, not knowing what the transcriptional consequences and

547
00:31:36.788 --> 00:31:40.488
hence what the clinical consequences are of activating Rb

548
00:31:40.568 --> 00:31:41.448
in breast cancers.

549
00:31:43.048 --> 00:31:46.948
So to look at this, our lab really set out with the primary goal of trying

550
00:31:46.988 --> 00:31:50.188
to find a good way to map Rb's genome-wide

551
00:31:50.248 --> 00:31:53.988
distribution on the chromatin. And we turned to this more

552
00:31:54.028 --> 00:31:56.338
modern epigenetic profiling method, CUT&amp;RUN.

553
00:31:57.008 --> 00:32:00.468
And with CUT&amp;RUN, we've been able to generate some robust

554
00:32:00.848 --> 00:32:04.608
genome-wide maps of Rb chromatin occupancy in breast cancer cells.

555
00:32:06.068 --> 00:32:09.828
We first proved that this is indeed a specific Rb CUT&amp;RUN

556
00:32:09.868 --> 00:32:13.728
signal because when we knock out Rb, we lose all signal, and we went on to

557
00:32:13.768 --> 00:32:17.368
then ask the question, how does Rb activation with CDK4/6

558
00:32:17.408 --> 00:32:20.068
inhibition change its distribution on the chromatin?

559
00:32:21.128 --> 00:32:24.708
So as you can imagine, when we treat with CDK4/6 inhibitors, we see a reduction in

560
00:32:24.788 --> 00:32:27.808
Rb phosphorylation, we see accumulation of cells in G1,

561
00:32:28.608 --> 00:32:32.588
and what we also see is a marked increase in chromatin-bound

562
00:32:32.748 --> 00:32:36.108
Rb, thousands of regions gaining Rb binding,

563
00:32:36.968 --> 00:32:39.248
very few regions losing Rb binding.

564
00:32:39.688 --> 00:32:43.448
So activation of Rb is basically associated with a widespread

565
00:32:43.468 --> 00:32:45.568
distribution of Rb across the genome.

566
00:32:45.968 --> 00:32:48.928
And I guess that's consistent with the old notion that it is this

567
00:32:49.008 --> 00:32:51.988
hypophosphorylated active form of Rb that is the

568
00:32:52.008 --> 00:32:54.188
chromatin-associated form of Rb.

569
00:32:56.028 --> 00:32:59.428
So we then asked the question, well, where are these binding events occurring?

570
00:32:59.748 --> 00:33:02.997
And what we found in these two cell line models was that the majority, about

571
00:33:02.997 --> 00:33:06.428
three-quarters of Rb binding events are happening over gene promoters.

572
00:33:06.948 --> 00:33:10.928
And this is looking at over 10,000 different regions throughout the genome in

573
00:33:10.938 --> 00:33:14.468
these cells. So it's a much broader promoter landscape than just the

574
00:33:14.528 --> 00:33:17.908
classical cell cycle genes that we typically think about.

575
00:33:19.108 --> 00:33:22.888
And importantly, a substantial fraction is also happening at non-promoter

576
00:33:22.948 --> 00:33:26.818
regions. Thousands of non-promoter regions are also gaining Rb binding, and this

577
00:33:26.868 --> 00:33:30.268
is, to us, very interesting because Rb function at these

578
00:33:30.328 --> 00:33:33.408
non-promoter regions has essentially never been explored.

579
00:33:34.388 --> 00:33:38.248
And we confirmed these findings by developing assays to map Rb in

580
00:33:38.328 --> 00:33:42.318
vivo. So this is a PDX model of hormone receptor-positive breast cancer,

581
00:33:42.388 --> 00:33:45.628
and again, we see very similar redistribution of Rb over the

582
00:33:45.648 --> 00:33:49.548
chromatin with treatment. And to our knowledge, this on the right is the first

583
00:33:49.557 --> 00:33:53.468
time that Rb distribution on chromatin has ever been mapped

584
00:33:53.528 --> 00:33:56.188
in any tissue context whatsoever.

585
00:33:58.328 --> 00:34:01.668
So then we asked, okay, let's start with the promoter binding events first and see

586
00:34:01.728 --> 00:34:04.388
if they do in fact show the Rb biology that we expect.

587
00:34:05.088 --> 00:34:08.768
And so when we look at the promoters that gain Rb binding after CDK4/6

588
00:34:08.948 --> 00:34:12.468
inhibitor treatment, we found strong enrichment for E2F motifs,

589
00:34:13.508 --> 00:34:15.649
consistent with the role of Rb, I guess, in

590
00:34:16.649 --> 00:34:18.629
repressing E2F-mediated transcription.

591
00:34:19.828 --> 00:34:23.808
Ontologically, those genes were heavily enriched for cell cycle processes and

592
00:34:23.848 --> 00:34:27.328
of course, the E2F target genes were heavily repressed by treatment.

593
00:34:27.368 --> 00:34:31.188
So at least this confirms our approach is capturing the canonical

594
00:34:31.288 --> 00:34:35.248
functions of Rb at cell cycle gene promoters, but it also tells us that

595
00:34:35.288 --> 00:34:39.258
there's a much broader chromatin landscape that Rb is occupying that

596
00:34:39.328 --> 00:34:40.408
we don't yet understand.

597
00:34:41.308 --> 00:34:44.808
So just to illustrate that more concretely here, here's just some examples of

598
00:34:44.948 --> 00:34:48.908
Rb accumulating at the promoters of cell cycle genes

599
00:34:48.948 --> 00:34:52.548
after treatment. And you can also see at those same promoters that there's

600
00:34:52.589 --> 00:34:56.109
reduced H3K27 acetylation, which is reduced transcriptional

601
00:34:56.169 --> 00:34:59.948
activity, and that's consistent with Rb's known role to

602
00:35:00.008 --> 00:35:03.688
recruit histone deacetylases to cell cycle

603
00:35:03.728 --> 00:35:06.008
promoters to repress gene expression.

604
00:35:09.028 --> 00:35:12.508
But we then were really interested in what's going on at these non-promoter sites

605
00:35:13.008 --> 00:35:16.988
that are gaining Rb binding after CDK4/6 inhibitor treatment, because unlike

606
00:35:17.038 --> 00:35:21.028
the promoter sites that we've looked at, these regions show, interestingly, a very

607
00:35:21.068 --> 00:35:21.848
different pattern.

608
00:35:22.848 --> 00:35:26.428
What we found here was that these

609
00:35:26.468 --> 00:35:29.368
non-promoter sites where Rb bound were marked by

610
00:35:29.528 --> 00:35:33.268
H3K27 acetylation, and in fact, the level of

611
00:35:33.408 --> 00:35:35.808
H3K27 acetylation increased

612
00:35:36.668 --> 00:35:37.348
with treatment.

613
00:35:38.548 --> 00:35:42.088
And also when we integrated with RNA-seq, we found that the

614
00:35:42.128 --> 00:35:45.768
genes that were located near these regions were more likely to be

615
00:35:45.828 --> 00:35:46.578
upregulated

616
00:35:47.488 --> 00:35:51.408
rather than suppressed. So instead of behaving like classic repressive

617
00:35:51.508 --> 00:35:55.258
sites, these regions seem to have the features of active enhancers,

618
00:35:55.608 --> 00:35:59.168
and their activity seems to increase with Rb

619
00:35:59.228 --> 00:36:00.228
recruitment.

620
00:36:01.848 --> 00:36:05.418
Importantly, these non-promoter Rb binding sites were highly consistent across

621
00:36:05.508 --> 00:36:09.288
models. So we saw the exact same regions gaining Rb binding in both

622
00:36:09.308 --> 00:36:13.288
cell line models and in the PDX model, as shown here, which suggests

623
00:36:13.298 --> 00:36:16.948
this is a very reproducible feature of Rb

624
00:36:16.988 --> 00:36:20.168
activation.And so we next asked the question: well, what are the

625
00:36:20.228 --> 00:36:22.688
genes associated with these sites?

626
00:36:23.568 --> 00:36:27.428
And I guess somewhat unexpectedly, across all the data sets

627
00:36:27.438 --> 00:36:31.108
that we looked at in all conditions, in vitro and in vivo, with two different

628
00:36:31.168 --> 00:36:32.558
CDK4/6 inhibitors,

629
00:36:33.528 --> 00:36:37.468
we found that the non-promoter sites gaining Rb binding were heavily

630
00:36:37.508 --> 00:36:40.708
enriched for proximity to estrogen response genes.

631
00:36:41.688 --> 00:36:45.468
And even when we restricted the analysis to those sites which gained Rb

632
00:36:45.668 --> 00:36:49.548
binding and where the nearby gene was significantly upregulated, again, the

633
00:36:49.608 --> 00:36:51.508
top hit was estrogen response.

634
00:36:53.488 --> 00:36:57.188
So here's some examples. There's some classic estrogen receptor target

635
00:36:57.228 --> 00:37:00.908
genes, and you can see increased Rb binding at non-promoter

636
00:37:00.968 --> 00:37:03.908
regions located within the gene or near the gene.

637
00:37:04.368 --> 00:37:07.848
And although I told you we found this estrogen response signal by looking at the

638
00:37:07.888 --> 00:37:11.728
non-promoter sites binding Rb, we also often

639
00:37:11.828 --> 00:37:15.777
saw some increase in Rb binding at the promoters of these genes

640
00:37:16.148 --> 00:37:18.688
as well. Now, these are not classical ER target genes,

641
00:37:19.548 --> 00:37:23.168
but it's suggesting that Rb is, in addition to ER target genes, being

642
00:37:23.208 --> 00:37:27.148
recruited to both enhancer and promoter regions around this set of

643
00:37:27.328 --> 00:37:28.828
estrogen response genes as well.

644
00:37:31.348 --> 00:37:35.088
So having seen Rb being recruited to these regions

645
00:37:35.168 --> 00:37:38.768
around ER target genes, and having seen that increase in

646
00:37:38.808 --> 00:37:42.258
H3K27 acetylation at the non-promoter regions where Rb was

647
00:37:42.288 --> 00:37:43.108
bound,

648
00:37:44.008 --> 00:37:47.628
we asked the question: are these ER target genes being upregulated by

649
00:37:47.728 --> 00:37:51.618
treatment? And so we looked at this in multiple systems, first of all, in three

650
00:37:51.668 --> 00:37:54.278
different cell lines, just using RNA sequencing,

651
00:37:55.088 --> 00:37:56.268
in PDX models,

652
00:37:57.388 --> 00:38:01.108
and also in a unique clinical cohort of patients

653
00:38:01.228 --> 00:38:04.848
treated with CDK4/6 inhibitor monotherapy, where we had paired

654
00:38:04.908 --> 00:38:06.068
biopsies before

655
00:38:06.928 --> 00:38:10.528
and after treatment. And in each of these three systems,

656
00:38:10.928 --> 00:38:14.408
expression profiling showed that the top upregulated gene set

657
00:38:15.248 --> 00:38:19.088
was the estrogen response. And the clinical data is, I think, particularly powerful

658
00:38:19.108 --> 00:38:22.668
here because getting paired biopsies before and after the

659
00:38:22.688 --> 00:38:26.367
CDK4/6 inhibitor monotherapy is a very difficult thing to do.

660
00:38:27.047 --> 00:38:29.808
And here we have these matched paired samples, not only from

661
00:38:30.768 --> 00:38:34.268
treated patients, from also from a group of patients who had no treatment, which

662
00:38:34.328 --> 00:38:37.248
means that the data we're generating is really quite robust in showing us

663
00:38:37.268 --> 00:38:38.748
treatment-specific effects.

664
00:38:41.808 --> 00:38:45.768
So at this point, we have clear evidence that Rb is being recruited around

665
00:38:45.808 --> 00:38:49.388
these ER target genes, and we show that these genes are being upregulated.

666
00:38:49.948 --> 00:38:53.908
But we really wanted to understand whether or not Rb recruitment to these

667
00:38:53.948 --> 00:38:57.868
regions is directly responsible for the upregulation of

668
00:38:57.888 --> 00:38:58.508
those genes.

669
00:38:59.808 --> 00:39:03.348
So first we just knocked out Rb globally, and we found that the

670
00:39:03.388 --> 00:39:05.128
induction of the estrogen response

671
00:39:06.088 --> 00:39:09.628
is no longer seen. And that's encouraging, but this is difficult to

672
00:39:09.668 --> 00:39:13.628
interpret because in these sorts of cells, when you knock out Rb, you

673
00:39:13.708 --> 00:39:16.728
disrupt multiple aspects of CDK4/6 inhibitor response.

674
00:39:16.768 --> 00:39:19.308
The cells even start cycling in response to drug.

675
00:39:19.788 --> 00:39:23.548
And so it's hard to interpret whether what we're showing is relating to a direct

676
00:39:23.728 --> 00:39:26.428
chromatin resident function of Rb.

677
00:39:27.388 --> 00:39:29.568
So to try and answer this more concretely,

678
00:39:30.548 --> 00:39:33.868
we took a more targeted approach, and we used a method called

679
00:39:34.068 --> 00:39:37.688
H3K27 acetylation HiChIP, and this allows us to

680
00:39:37.768 --> 00:39:41.488
map physical interactions between promoters and

681
00:39:41.548 --> 00:39:44.508
enhancers that are marked by active chromatin.

682
00:39:44.738 --> 00:39:48.708
And so we can basically link those distal regulatory elements to the very

683
00:39:48.728 --> 00:39:52.538
genes that they're controlling. And using this, we could identify

684
00:39:52.888 --> 00:39:56.748
some specific enhancers which were new loops

685
00:39:56.818 --> 00:40:00.648
that newly formed upon treatment, and which showed increased

686
00:40:00.748 --> 00:40:04.588
Rb binding at the time of treatment and looped to the promoters

687
00:40:04.728 --> 00:40:06.328
of estrogen response target genes.

688
00:40:06.708 --> 00:40:10.688
And using CRISPR-Cas9, we selectively disrupted

689
00:40:10.698 --> 00:40:14.668
those individual enhancers. So we're not perturbing Rb globally,

690
00:40:14.768 --> 00:40:18.548
we're not perturbing its effects on the cell cycle, but specifically looking at its

691
00:40:18.588 --> 00:40:22.448
function at those loci. And what we found was that disruption of

692
00:40:22.568 --> 00:40:22.988
Rb

693
00:40:24.088 --> 00:40:27.408
at those enhancers or Rb binding had no impact on gene

694
00:40:27.468 --> 00:40:31.288
expression in the basal conditions, but it did

695
00:40:31.348 --> 00:40:34.907
impair the upregulation of these estrogen response target

696
00:40:34.928 --> 00:40:38.708
genes in the face of treatment. And this was even evident at the

697
00:40:38.748 --> 00:40:42.648
protein level here. So looking at the classic gene cyclin D, for example, where the

698
00:40:42.708 --> 00:40:46.148
upregulation of cyclin D is significantly less if these

699
00:40:46.238 --> 00:40:48.708
Rb-bound enhancers are treated with CRISPR.

700
00:40:49.318 --> 00:40:52.918
And so this collectively, I think this data now really do support this model in

701
00:40:52.948 --> 00:40:56.888
which Rb binding at enhancers is playing a direct functional

702
00:40:56.988 --> 00:40:59.428
role in driving this estrogen response program.

703
00:41:01.748 --> 00:41:02.748
So having seen that,

704
00:41:03.808 --> 00:41:07.408
and having seen that these drugs are inducing this ER transcriptional program,

705
00:41:08.828 --> 00:41:11.168
I guess we started to wonder what this could mean for patients.

706
00:41:11.848 --> 00:41:15.798
Because in particular, we wondered whether this could explain what we see all the

707
00:41:15.798 --> 00:41:19.548
time, which is, as I said before, CDK4/6 inhibitors have

708
00:41:19.588 --> 00:41:22.668
modest impact when given as monotherapy, but very

709
00:41:23.008 --> 00:41:26.608
powerful efficacy when given together with endocrine therapy, which would

710
00:41:26.648 --> 00:41:28.568
block this estrogen response.

711
00:41:29.458 --> 00:41:32.748
And we've known for many years that higher levels of ER target gene

712
00:41:32.808 --> 00:41:36.548
expression in general are linked to better endocrine

713
00:41:36.608 --> 00:41:39.948
sensitivity, and so it raises the possibility, I guess,

714
00:41:40.488 --> 00:41:43.288
that by inducing this ER target gene program,

715
00:41:43.768 --> 00:41:47.248
CDK4/6 inhibitors are basically making cells more endocrine

716
00:41:47.308 --> 00:41:51.008
sensitive. And we saw similar things in our own systems.

717
00:41:51.468 --> 00:41:55.408
For example, we found that when we treat cells with a combination of CDK4/6

718
00:41:55.488 --> 00:41:58.988
inhibitors and endocrine therapy, we get much deeper

719
00:41:59.028 --> 00:42:02.868
suppression of cell cycle genes compared to just using a CDK4/6

720
00:42:02.908 --> 00:42:06.728
inhibitor alone. And this is associated with deeper

721
00:42:06.788 --> 00:42:09.268
suppression of S-phase entry

722
00:42:10.128 --> 00:42:13.868
and also prevention of cell outgrowth in long-term in vitro

723
00:42:13.928 --> 00:42:17.788
assays. So it basically raises the possibility that this

724
00:42:17.948 --> 00:42:18.828
Rb-driven

725
00:42:19.668 --> 00:42:23.428
estrogen response program that we're seeing may be linked to the

726
00:42:23.468 --> 00:42:25.328
therapeutic synergy that we're all familiar

727
00:42:25.368 --> 00:42:29.338
with.So we then began to ask, well,

728
00:42:29.378 --> 00:42:31.718
which part of this ER program

729
00:42:32.798 --> 00:42:36.518
might be working to actually limit the full extent of cell

730
00:42:36.598 --> 00:42:40.538
cycle arrest? And we focused on cyclin D1, which I've talked to you about already.

731
00:42:40.548 --> 00:42:42.778
And we focused on cyclin D1 for a few different reasons.

732
00:42:42.818 --> 00:42:45.238
First of all, it's a well-known ER target gene.

733
00:42:46.058 --> 00:42:49.798
We've shown, and others have shown, that it's upregulated by CDK4/6 inhibitors,

734
00:42:49.838 --> 00:42:53.308
that this is dependent on ER, and it's also dependent, this

735
00:42:53.358 --> 00:42:56.828
upregulation, on Rb. And

736
00:42:56.858 --> 00:43:00.617
importantly, as I showed you earlier, we showed that when we disrupted the Rb-bound

737
00:43:00.658 --> 00:43:04.458
enhancers around cyclin D, it prevented the upregulation of cyclin D

738
00:43:04.478 --> 00:43:08.238
protein. So, this gave us a specific candidate to

739
00:43:08.278 --> 00:43:08.858
focus on

740
00:43:09.858 --> 00:43:13.078
within this broader estrogen response program that could be clinically relevant.

741
00:43:13.998 --> 00:43:17.368
So we asked the question, well, what happens if we remove this specific signal?

742
00:43:17.388 --> 00:43:20.138
Rather than blocking ER, if we just take away cyclin D1.

743
00:43:21.218 --> 00:43:24.868
So the first thing we found is that if you knock down cyclin D1, in addition to

744
00:43:24.918 --> 00:43:28.038
giving a CDK4/6 inhibitor, it leads to a much deeper

745
00:43:28.058 --> 00:43:31.778
suppression of cell cycle genes compared to CDK4/6

746
00:43:31.818 --> 00:43:32.688
inhibitors alone,

747
00:43:33.598 --> 00:43:37.558
suggesting that this induction of cyclin D that we're getting may be acting to

748
00:43:37.618 --> 00:43:41.498
partially counteract the effects of Rb

749
00:43:41.538 --> 00:43:45.478
activation. And so basically that's led us to this model,

750
00:43:45.838 --> 00:43:49.528
which says that when we treat our breast cancer cells with CDK4/6 inhibitors,

751
00:43:49.938 --> 00:43:53.668
yes, active Rb is going to E2F factors and repressing

752
00:43:53.738 --> 00:43:57.338
target genes, but at the same time, it is being

753
00:43:57.358 --> 00:44:01.348
recruited to other enhancers and promoters at ER target genes

754
00:44:01.358 --> 00:44:04.948
where it's driving their expression, and that program includes

755
00:44:04.998 --> 00:44:07.178
pro-proliferative genes such as cyclin D.

756
00:44:08.188 --> 00:44:12.008
And in this setting, really the fascinating thing to me is that Rb is doing two

757
00:44:12.038 --> 00:44:14.838
things at once. On the one hand, it's enforcing cell cycle arrest.

758
00:44:15.278 --> 00:44:18.418
But at the same time, it is activating a program that can push back

759
00:44:18.498 --> 00:44:20.278
against that arrest.

760
00:44:21.198 --> 00:44:24.788
Now, if you happen to have good endocrine therapy, which fortunately we often do,

761
00:44:25.138 --> 00:44:29.058
you can neutralize that second component and get deep

762
00:44:29.098 --> 00:44:31.638
cell cycle suppression and potent therapeutic synergy.

763
00:44:31.668 --> 00:44:35.658
And this is probably a new and quite simple way of thinking about the synergy that

764
00:44:35.698 --> 00:44:37.218
we see in the clinic all the time.

765
00:44:39.738 --> 00:44:43.218
What we've also done a lot of work on, I don't have time to show the actual data

