00:55:25.474 --> 00:55:26.204
Because we then have to-

968
00:55:26.254 --> 00:55:26.814
Yep

969
00:55:26.823 --> 00:55:27.874
... to prove that

970
00:55:28.674 --> 00:55:32.574
well, we need to profile the distribution of each E2F

971
00:55:32.614 --> 00:55:36.334
factor on the chromatin pre- and post-treatment in these cells.

972
00:55:36.974 --> 00:55:40.494
Sometimes you'll see multiple factors at the same position at

973
00:55:40.654 --> 00:55:43.294
once and try to dissect out

974
00:55:44.414 --> 00:55:47.694
RB E2F individual, E2F binding at each of those regions.

975
00:55:47.714 --> 00:55:47.804
It's-

976
00:55:47.994 --> 00:55:51.754
That's one way of doing it. The other way of doing it is a proteomic approach,

977
00:55:51.834 --> 00:55:52.394
which is where

978
00:55:53.394 --> 00:55:57.044
if you take RB and you co-precipitate it under drug-induced

979
00:55:57.094 --> 00:56:00.854
conditions or not, do you see a different subset of E2Fs

980
00:56:00.894 --> 00:56:01.454
being bound?

981
00:56:01.914 --> 00:56:03.853
Yeah, that is actually a good idea. Thank you.

982
00:56:04.714 --> 00:56:05.834
Last question.

983
00:56:06.634 --> 00:56:07.934
Yeah. Great talk.

984
00:56:07.974 --> 00:56:08.394
Thank you, Phil.

985
00:56:08.914 --> 00:56:12.534
My question relates to just in patient samples, have you

986
00:56:12.614 --> 00:56:13.014
seen

987
00:56:13.914 --> 00:56:17.574
or analyzed those that have failed CDK4/6 inhibitor

988
00:56:17.654 --> 00:56:21.434
therapy and looked at upregulation of these EPR target genes in

989
00:56:21.474 --> 00:56:22.284
those samples?

990
00:56:22.374 --> 00:56:23.794
Yeah, that's a great question, Phil.

991
00:56:24.734 --> 00:56:27.514
We haven't. So doing the RB

992
00:56:28.374 --> 00:56:30.234
chromatin mapping in tissue,

993
00:56:31.974 --> 00:56:34.454
is something that, as I showed you, we can do.

994
00:56:35.054 --> 00:56:38.994
We've done it in PDX tissue, and one of our big frontiers now is

995
00:56:39.054 --> 00:56:41.054
to start doing this in human tumors.

996
00:56:43.174 --> 00:56:46.954
So far, to be honest, our ability to do it in tissue requires fresh tissue.

997
00:56:47.854 --> 00:56:51.674
So not even tissue that's been viably frozen. We need fresh tissue.

998
00:56:52.214 --> 00:56:52.654
And so,

999
00:56:53.554 --> 00:56:57.294
we've not been able to do it in the setting of clinical

1000
00:56:57.394 --> 00:57:01.094
samples, let alone with respect to response or resistance.

1001
00:57:01.324 --> 00:57:01.904
Yeah. Thanks.

1002
00:57:02.414 --> 00:57:04.313
All right. Thank you, Jonathan.

1003
00:57:07.234 --> 00:57:11.034
All right, so our last speaker is Nolan Prettykid from

1004
00:57:11.094 --> 00:57:13.554
the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.

1005
00:57:14.194 --> 00:57:18.134
He works there with Todd Golub and others, and as I said, he's

1006
00:57:18.214 --> 00:57:20.854
also a breast medical oncologist, but doing some

1007
00:57:21.714 --> 00:57:25.614
outstanding genomics and computational research, in this case, looking at RNA

1008
00:57:25.694 --> 00:57:28.034
fusions and novel drivers.

1009
00:57:30.154 --> 00:57:33.934
Okay. All right. So firstly, thank you to the organizers and Dr.

1010
00:57:34.154 --> 00:57:35.274
Pru and Dr. Arteaga

1011
00:57:36.294 --> 00:57:38.354
for allowing me to present this work at ACR.

1012
00:57:38.534 --> 00:57:39.554
And I'm going to tell you about

1013
00:57:40.434 --> 00:57:44.014
our attempts to build a programmable nucleic acid sensing system

1014
00:57:44.634 --> 00:57:46.494
that might be useful for cancer.

1015
00:57:47.694 --> 00:57:49.414
And these are my disclosures.

1016
00:57:51.914 --> 00:57:55.814
And I'm going to start relatively simply, and I think it's safe to say that a major

1017
00:57:55.854 --> 00:57:59.474
goal of oncology is really to build medicines that eliminate cancer cells while

1018
00:57:59.514 --> 00:58:03.364
sparing healthy tissue. And most drugs, as we know, do this with

1019
00:58:03.434 --> 00:58:07.194
kind of a narrow therapeutic window, where they preferentially kill cancer cells

1020
00:58:07.494 --> 00:58:08.874
slightly more than healthy cells.

1021
00:58:09.614 --> 00:58:13.554
But really truly cancer-specific therapies and these magic bullet targets

1022
00:58:13.614 --> 00:58:17.534
like BCR-ABL in CML, HER2 positive breast

1023
00:58:17.614 --> 00:58:17.954
cancer,

1024
00:58:18.814 --> 00:58:22.254
they're actually quite rare when you look across solid tumors, yet are historically

1025
00:58:22.314 --> 00:58:26.274
the most impactful for patients. So the question is really how can we

1026
00:58:26.314 --> 00:58:30.104
increase this reservoir of truly cancer-specific targets?

1027
00:58:31.794 --> 00:58:35.154
And I think it's also safe to say that the most distinguishing feature of a cancer

1028
00:58:35.174 --> 00:58:38.854
cell is the genome itself. And you can see here a spectral

1029
00:58:38.874 --> 00:58:42.074
karyogram of chromosomes of a normal cell where each chromosome is painted a

1030
00:58:42.094 --> 00:58:43.894
different color, and it's clean.

1031
00:58:44.794 --> 00:58:48.294
And here is a breast cancer cell, where you can see the DNA has been amplified,

1032
00:58:48.374 --> 00:58:51.044
inverted, deleted, and rearranged into one another.

1033
00:58:52.154 --> 00:58:55.094
And everywhere that there are essentially two colors touching, and there can be

1034
00:58:55.234 --> 00:58:58.844
hundreds to thousands of these in an individual breast cancer, is

1035
00:58:58.914 --> 00:59:02.054
a barcode that exists only in cancer cells.

1036
00:59:02.654 --> 00:59:05.834
And the question of my postdoc, and also

1037
00:59:06.214 --> 00:59:09.954
increasingly my career, is how can we think about better exploiting these

1038
00:59:10.134 --> 00:59:13.794
cancer-specific breakpoints with recent advances in nucleic acid

1039
00:59:13.814 --> 00:59:15.034
targeting technologies?

1040
00:59:16.874 --> 00:59:20.854
And the target that we chose first are fusion genes or fusion RNAs, and as

1041
00:59:20.894 --> 00:59:24.424
we all know, it's when two genes are normally separated in space, they're fused

1042
00:59:24.454 --> 00:59:27.804
together at the DNA level, but they can also be expressed as RNA or

1043
00:59:27.814 --> 00:59:31.594
protein. And it's really changed the world for these patients when there is a

1044
00:59:31.654 --> 00:59:35.434
kinase involved because we can build small molecules to target them

1045
00:59:35.474 --> 00:59:39.254
selectively. At the same time, it's an uncomfortable fact that there are

1046
00:59:39.294 --> 00:59:41.134
many fusions that we have not cracked,

1047
00:59:42.294 --> 00:59:44.494
some examples being in sarcoma,

1048
00:59:45.334 --> 00:59:46.314
and this is unacceptable.

1049
00:59:47.794 --> 00:59:51.014
And at the same time in breast cancer, there are fusions that drive endocrine

1050
00:59:51.054 --> 00:59:52.994
therapy resistance in the advanced setting.

1051
00:59:53.594 --> 00:59:57.524
And we've shown that ER fusions can occur likely more frequently than previously

1052
00:59:57.754 --> 01:00:00.194
thought at a frequency of 9 to 10%.

1053
01:00:01.734 --> 01:00:05.614
And at the same time, there's private fusions, so N of one fusions that

1054
01:00:05.654 --> 01:00:09.634
might be more common in breast cancer than previously appreciated, and they often

1055
01:00:09.674 --> 01:00:13.294
can occur very early in cancer development, suggesting they may be truncal

1056
01:00:13.394 --> 01:00:17.254
targets or more homogeneous targets in a traditionally very heterogeneous disease.

1057
01:00:18.314 --> 01:00:21.814
So the first thing that we did is just quantify fusion RNAs in metastatic breast

1058
01:00:21.874 --> 01:00:25.534
cancer. So we used a cohort of 423 metastatic breast cancer

1059
01:00:25.594 --> 01:00:28.974
cases. Importantly, we used frozen tissue, which increases your sensitivity of

1060
01:00:28.994 --> 01:00:31.514
calling fusions by about sevenfold.

1061
01:00:31.994 --> 01:00:35.314
And the bottom line is that they're common in breast cancer, with basal and HER2

1062
01:00:35.354 --> 01:00:39.314
having the most unique fusions per cancer, with LumB and LumA

1063
01:00:39.354 --> 01:00:39.734
behind.

1064
01:00:40.854 --> 01:00:44.754
Greater than 90% of breast cancer cases do have a fusion RNA that we're able

1065
01:00:44.794 --> 01:00:48.482
to detect.And when you look across

1066
01:00:48.842 --> 01:00:52.772
cancers, common cancers, breast cancer again stands out among the

1067
01:00:52.862 --> 01:00:53.942
top, likely because

1068
01:00:54.782 --> 01:00:58.612
of a larger degree of genomic instability that's been confirmed with whole

1069
01:00:58.662 --> 01:00:59.802
genome sequencing studies.

1070
01:01:01.942 --> 01:01:05.382
And if you look at which ones are truly highly expressed, that might be

1071
01:01:05.682 --> 01:01:09.522
potential targets for a nucleic acid therapy, and you just define a simple

1072
01:01:09.582 --> 01:01:13.462
outlier threshold, 33% of metastatic breast cancers express at

1073
01:01:13.502 --> 01:01:16.602
least one fusion, sometimes multiple, relatively highly.

1074
01:01:16.622 --> 01:01:20.082
And these often involve driver-related genes such as ESR1 and

1075
01:01:20.142 --> 01:01:24.132
PI3K pathway members. But the majority of them, 98%, are

1076
01:01:24.162 --> 01:01:27.402
private. So whether or not they're drivers or passengers, we do not know.

1077
01:01:27.422 --> 01:01:30.601
But the point is that they're there and highly expressed.

1078
01:01:31.672 --> 01:01:35.432
These fusions that are highly expressed can also be preserved in a

1079
01:01:35.462 --> 01:01:37.882
patient that's had many lines of therapy.

1080
01:01:38.382 --> 01:01:41.882
So this is a Sankey plot that shows two truncal fusion RNAs that we

1081
01:01:41.942 --> 01:01:45.462
identified that was present in the breast primary, but at the time of a rapid

1082
01:01:45.522 --> 01:01:49.502
autopsy case, was preserved in every single metastatic tissue that was sampled

1083
01:01:49.542 --> 01:01:53.001
from this patient and absent from a matched normal tissue.

1084
01:01:53.382 --> 01:01:57.112
Again, suggesting that if we can think of a way to target these more thoughtfully,

1085
01:01:57.822 --> 01:02:01.502
it might be a way to cut through the heterogeneity in the advanced disease setting.

1086
01:02:03.062 --> 01:02:06.942
So a concept that we came up with is if we can use these nucleotides not as

1087
01:02:06.962 --> 01:02:10.832
direct biological targets, but almost like a molecular switch or trigger for a

1088
01:02:10.862 --> 01:02:14.622
modular therapeutic effect. So you can imagine you have a cancer-specific

1089
01:02:14.642 --> 01:02:18.622
barcode, develop some technology where it detects whether or not it's in

1090
01:02:18.662 --> 01:02:21.932
a cancer cell, and triggers something that would kill the cancer cell.

1091
01:02:22.482 --> 01:02:25.782
And conceptually, as I had mentioned, it needs to be patient scalable because

1092
01:02:25.802 --> 01:02:29.412
98% of these are patient-specific and

1093
01:02:29.462 --> 01:02:32.712
amenable, and we want it to be amenable to any cancer-specific nucleotide,

1094
01:02:33.102 --> 01:02:35.462
regardless of whether or not it's a passenger or a driver.

1095
01:02:37.482 --> 01:02:41.172
So there was a technology that caught our eye, and it's RNA editing,

1096
01:02:41.562 --> 01:02:45.122
and the premise is that you design a guide RNA that's complementary to a target in

1097
01:02:45.142 --> 01:02:48.762
the cell. This guide RNA has an intentional C to A mismatch,

1098
01:02:49.122 --> 01:02:53.002
and there's a protein that exists within cells, you don't have to introduce it like

1099
01:02:53.042 --> 01:02:56.521
CRISPR, called ADAR, that selectively deanimates that

1100
01:02:56.542 --> 01:02:58.742
mismatch on the adenosine into an inosine.

1101
01:02:59.642 --> 01:03:03.562
And it's been used to correct genetic mutations at

1102
01:03:03.602 --> 01:03:06.942
the RNA level, and there's some Phase 1 and Phase 2 studies being performed.

1103
01:03:08.362 --> 01:03:12.322
Our collaborators developed a twist on this technology where you make

1104
01:03:12.362 --> 01:03:12.942
the

1105
01:03:14.322 --> 01:03:16.862
mismatch not in the target, but in the guide.

1106
01:03:17.522 --> 01:03:21.442
And you make it so that it is in a trinucleotide context that is a

1107
01:03:21.522 --> 01:03:25.202
stop codon. So when it binds to its fusion RNA target,

1108
01:03:25.842 --> 01:03:29.302
the deamination happens on the guide, and it turns a stop

1109
01:03:29.362 --> 01:03:32.402
codon into an in-frame codon, essentially

1110
01:03:32.462 --> 01:03:36.202
ungating the translation of a downstream protein payload.

1111
01:03:36.842 --> 01:03:40.282
And we use this to sense things like to define cell states.

1112
01:03:40.682 --> 01:03:44.522
But we thought perhaps you can use this as a cancer-sensing protein

1113
01:03:44.622 --> 01:03:48.062
payload switch and express something downstream that is toxic.

1114
01:03:48.562 --> 01:03:51.622
And this technology was developed by Dr. Fei Chen and Dr.

1115
01:03:51.862 --> 01:03:52.822
Jeremy Koop at the Broad.

1116
01:03:55.042 --> 01:03:58.502
So we got to work and designed fusion-targeting RNA sensors, and we used two

1117
01:03:58.622 --> 01:04:02.442
broad architectures. Linear sensors, which essentially

1118
01:04:02.502 --> 01:04:04.862
hybridize directly across the fusion breakpoint.

1119
01:04:05.302 --> 01:04:09.202
And we also designed a new type of sensor called a gap sensor, where we

1120
01:04:09.242 --> 01:04:10.382
have one portion of the

1121
01:04:11.202 --> 01:04:15.002
guide RNA that binds to the five-prime partner and another portion that binds to

1122
01:04:15.062 --> 01:04:18.642
the three-prime partner. And the thought is that in three-dimensional space, you'll

1123
01:04:18.682 --> 01:04:22.342
still form that double-stranded RNA duplex that recruits ADAR and flips the

1124
01:04:22.382 --> 01:04:24.622
switch for the downstream protein payload.

1125
01:04:25.982 --> 01:04:29.762
So the first thing that we did is we tested this in the most contrived model, human

1126
01:04:29.782 --> 01:04:32.982
embryonic kidney cells, because they're easy to get a lot of DNA into.

1127
01:04:33.402 --> 01:04:36.722
And we targeted an ESR1 fusion, and we used a fluorescent reporter.

1128
01:04:37.622 --> 01:04:41.362
So we've transfected cells with an empty vector and those with the fusion, and this

1129
01:04:41.422 --> 01:04:44.221
is the fluorescence here. Blue do not have the fusion.

1130
01:04:44.512 --> 01:04:47.942
Red do have the fusion. These are different sensors on the

1131
01:04:48.162 --> 01:04:52.102
x-axis, and we found fairly selective protein expression using both

1132
01:04:52.162 --> 01:04:56.092
linear and gap sensor designs. And this is endpoint microscopy, showing

1133
01:04:56.142 --> 01:04:59.722
just the magnitude of effect that we see for selective protein

1134
01:04:59.782 --> 01:05:01.042
expression in this model.

1135
01:05:03.382 --> 01:05:06.602
Next, we needed to move to a more real-world model.

1136
01:05:06.742 --> 01:05:10.542
So we applied the same algorithm that we used to identify fusion RNAs in

1137
01:05:10.582 --> 01:05:14.122
patient tumors to human cell lines, and we found a highly

1138
01:05:14.162 --> 01:05:17.962
expressed ARFGAP2-Solf2 fusion in the MCF7 line.

1139
01:05:18.782 --> 01:05:22.682
We confirmed that this fusion exists using breakpoint spanning RT-PCR and defined a

1140
01:05:22.702 --> 01:05:26.382
real estate of about 1,000 base pairs surrounding the breakpoint to design sensors

1141
01:05:26.422 --> 01:05:26.882
against.

1142
01:05:28.062 --> 01:05:31.922
So this is the same experiment now moving to flow cytometry, targeting an

1143
01:05:31.962 --> 01:05:34.942
endogenously expressed fusion in MCF7 cells.

1144
01:05:35.402 --> 01:05:37.802
And we used the fusion negative line, MCF10A.

1145
01:05:38.532 --> 01:05:42.162
And this is the percent of mNeon expression in 10A, so a fusion negative line

1146
01:05:42.222 --> 01:05:45.942
versus the fusion positive line where we found selective protein expression

1147
01:05:46.622 --> 01:05:50.262
in cells that contain the fusion against an endogenous target.

1148
01:05:52.342 --> 01:05:55.482
So the next is we wanted to move beyond reporters to a more therapeutic

1149
01:05:55.562 --> 01:05:58.242
application, and we're interested in two broad therapeutic

1150
01:05:59.302 --> 01:06:02.182
payloads. You can imagine a rewiring payload that might be immune

1151
01:06:02.262 --> 01:06:06.162
stimulatory or a directly cytotoxic payload, and we decided to

1152
01:06:06.202 --> 01:06:08.082
start with a directly cytotoxic payload.

1153
01:06:09.242 --> 01:06:12.362
We decided to use a human-tested cytotoxic protein payload,

1154
01:06:12.522 --> 01:06:16.352
Icaspase9. And what this is, is a synthetic molecule that

1155
01:06:16.402 --> 01:06:20.112
has a dimerizing domain at the N-terminal region and

1156
01:06:20.342 --> 01:06:23.662
a caspase molecule in the C-terminal region.

1157
01:06:23.702 --> 01:06:27.302
You add a biologically inert AP1903 drug, it causes this to

1158
01:06:27.322 --> 01:06:29.082
dimerize and triggers apoptosis.

1159
01:06:29.472 --> 01:06:33.362
And this has been essentially used as a CAR T safety switch in pediatrics and

1160
01:06:33.422 --> 01:06:33.842
adults.

1161
01:06:35.622 --> 01:06:39.482
So we put our fusion targeting sensors, this time with

1162
01:06:39.542 --> 01:06:43.442
a cytotoxic payload in MCF7s. These are our controls on the right

1163
01:06:43.542 --> 01:06:46.302
where we have styrosporin, which is essentially our floor of

1164
01:06:47.882 --> 01:06:51.782
cancer cell killing. And we have a panel of NTCs here, and these

1165
01:06:51.862 --> 01:06:55.842
NTCs are non-targeting controls, and they are sensors

1166
01:06:55.882 --> 01:06:59.782
that target fusions not present in the cell line that we're targeting in

1167
01:06:59.822 --> 01:07:02.962
other contexts, and you can see the viability is around 100%.

1168
01:07:03.802 --> 01:07:07.262
And these are the fusion targeting sensors, and we were happy to see that both gap

1169
01:07:07.282 --> 01:07:11.062
and linear designs did cause a pretty profound decrease in cell viability in

1170
01:07:11.162 --> 01:07:14.762
MCF7s down to 80% at this one particular time

1171
01:07:14.822 --> 01:07:18.632
point.This is what the cells look like

1172
01:07:18.732 --> 01:07:19.202
when

1173
01:07:20.252 --> 01:07:24.162
transfected with the sensor. This is the NTC control, so it's targeting an ESR1

1174
01:07:24.192 --> 01:07:27.382
fusion that is not present in this line with the same cytotoxic

1175
01:07:27.412 --> 01:07:31.212
payload. And then this is the targeting sensor, so targeting the

1176
01:07:31.292 --> 01:07:34.972
RFGF2-SOX2 fusion that exists in this line, and you can see the cancer

1177
01:07:34.992 --> 01:07:38.912
cells undergo apoptosis. And then when you take the sensor

1178
01:07:39.472 --> 01:07:43.232
and you plug it into a cell line that does not have

1179
01:07:43.432 --> 01:07:43.932
the fusion,

1180
01:07:44.872 --> 01:07:46.872
there's minimal toxicity.

1181
01:07:48.312 --> 01:07:50.712
And then when you put the fusion into these cell lines,

1182
01:07:52.552 --> 01:07:56.412
we do see a modest effect, a decrease in viability, suggesting there is some

1183
01:07:56.472 --> 01:07:57.272
specificity here.

1184
01:07:58.832 --> 01:08:02.612
So, this is a clever trick that you can pull off in vitro, but there's

1185
01:08:02.692 --> 01:08:06.252
major challenges to overcome that we

1186
01:08:06.312 --> 01:08:09.802
are actively pursuing. One, we don't know the design rules of

1187
01:08:09.832 --> 01:08:12.232
why some sensors work better than others.

1188
01:08:12.272 --> 01:08:15.832
You could see the variability in the gap in linear sensors because we're testing

1189
01:08:15.872 --> 01:08:19.592
dozens at a time. So now, we're doing high throughput RNA

1190
01:08:19.632 --> 01:08:22.842
sensor screening in order to identify really the design rules for this

1191
01:08:22.873 --> 01:08:23.612
hybridization.

1192
01:08:24.632 --> 01:08:26.732
Delivery is always going to be an issue.

1193
01:08:27.413 --> 01:08:29.052
So we're collaborating with folks

1194
01:08:29.852 --> 01:08:33.822
in the viral nanoparticle antibody LNP field to see if we can deliver these

1195
01:08:33.852 --> 01:08:37.612
to a mouse in vivo. And then an interesting thing to think about is

1196
01:08:37.873 --> 01:08:41.672
what payload would you choose? We chose the most simple payload, which is a

1197
01:08:41.713 --> 01:08:45.333
directly cytotoxic payload, but you can imagine you can produce an immune

1198
01:08:45.392 --> 01:08:46.482
stimulatory payload,

1199
01:08:47.413 --> 01:08:50.442
drug baits, and even think of a synthetic payload that doesn't exist in the natural

1200
01:08:50.512 --> 01:08:50.852
world.

